hands_on_practices.solution:
A two-state continuous-time Markov chain with transition rates $\lambda$ from state $1$ to $2$ and $\mu$ from state $2$ to $1$ has generator matrix
$$
Q=\begin{pmatrix}
-\lambda  \lambda \\
\mu  -\mu
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
With $\lambda=2$ and $\mu=3$, this becomes
$$
Q=\begin{pmatrix}
-2  2 \\
3  -3
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
The uniformization rate is chosen as $\Lambda = \max_{i}|q_{ii}| = \max\{2,3\} = 3$. The embedded discrete-time transition matrix is
$$
P=I+\frac{1}{\Lambda}Q=I+\frac{1}{3}\begin{pmatrix}
-2  2 \\
3  -3
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
1-\frac{2}{3}  \frac{2}{3} \\
1  1-1
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{1}{3}  \frac{2}{3} \\
1  0
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
The two-step transition probability matrix is $P^{(2)}=P^{2}$.
$$
P^{2}=\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{1}{3}  \frac{2}{3} \\
1  0
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{1}{3}  \frac{2}{3} \\
1  0
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{1}{9}+\frac{2}{3}  \frac{2}{9}+0 \\
\frac{1}{3}+0  \frac{2}{3}+0
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{7}{9}  \frac{2}{9} \\
\frac{1}{3}  \frac{2}{3}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Therefore, the two-step transition probability matrix is as above.
